<% content_for :title, "#{@post[:title]} | devopsellence blog" %>

<main class="page page-article">
  <header class="article-header">
    <p class="article-back"><%= link_to "&larr; Blog".html_safe, blog_path %></p>
    <p class="article-series-label"><%= @post[:series] %> &mdash; Part <%= @post[:part] %> of 7</p>
    <h1><%= @post[:title] %></h1>
    <div class="article-meta">
      <time><%= @post[:date].strftime("%B %-d, %Y") %></time>
      <span><%= @post[:reading_time] %></span>
    </div>
  </header>

  <article class="article-body">

    <p>When you run <code>devopsellence deploy</code>, the CLI builds a Docker image, pushes it to a registry, and publishes a release. But the deploy isn't delivered to your servers through the control plane. Instead, the control plane signs a desired-state envelope, writes it to Google Cloud Storage, and steps out of the way. Agents on your servers pull from GCS, verify the cryptographic signature, pull the image from Artifact Registry, and reconcile containers locally.</p>

    <p>This article covers the full delivery pipeline: how envelopes are signed, how they're stored in GCS, how agents verify them, and how images flow through Artifact Registry.</p>

    <h2>The deploy flow</h2>

    <ol>
      <li><strong>Build &amp; push.</strong> The CLI builds a Docker image and pushes it to Google Artifact Registry using short-lived push credentials (~20 minutes, scoped to the organization's repository).</li>
      <li><strong>Publish.</strong> The CLI sends the release to the control plane. The control plane records it, advances the sequence number, and constructs a desired-state envelope.</li>
      <li><strong>Sign.</strong> The envelope is signed with RSA-PKCS1v15-SHA256. In production, the signing key lives in Cloud KMS &mdash; the private key never enters application memory. The signature is computed inside Google's HSMs.</li>
      <li><strong>Write to GCS.</strong> The signed envelope is written to Cloud Storage as an immutable, versioned object. A pointer file is updated atomically.</li>
      <li><strong>Agent reconcile.</strong> Every 2 seconds, agents check GCS for new state. They verify the signature, pull the image, resolve secrets, and reconcile containers.</li>
    </ol>

    <h2>Signed envelopes</h2>

    <p>Every desired-state envelope uses the <code>signed_desired_state.v1</code> format. The envelope contains everything the agent needs to verify authenticity and apply the deployment:</p>

    <div class="terminal">
      <div class="terminal-bar">
        <span class="dot dot-red"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-yellow"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-green"></span>
        <span class="terminal-bar-title">Envelope structure</span>
      </div>
      <div class="terminal-body">
        <pre class="config-pre"><code>{
  "format": "signed_desired_state.v1",
  "schema_version": 1,
  "algorithm": "RS256",
  "key_id": "desired_state:a1b2c3d4e5f6g7h8",
  "sequence": 42,
  "issued_at": "2026-04-04T12:00:00Z",
  "expires_at": "2026-04-05T12:00:00Z",
  "payload_sha256": "abc123...",
  "organization_bundle_token": "...",
  "environment_bundle_token": "...",
  "node_bundle_token": "...",
  "signature": "base64url-encoded RS256 signature",
  "payload_json": "{ ... full desired state ... }"
}</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>The <code>payload_json</code> contains the full deployment spec: container definitions, environment variables, <code>gsm://</code> secret references, volume mounts, health check config, ingress settings, and the release command if set.</p>

    <h3>What the agent verifies</h3>

    <p>Before applying any changes, the agent runs a strict verification chain:</p>

    <ol>
      <li><strong>Payload integrity.</strong> Compute SHA256 of <code>payload_json</code> and verify it matches <code>payload_sha256</code>. Rejects tampered payloads.</li>
      <li><strong>Timestamps.</strong> Verify <code>issued_at</code> and <code>expires_at</code>. Envelopes have a 1-day TTL. Expired envelopes are rejected.</li>
      <li><strong>Sequence number.</strong> Verify the sequence is &ge; the current sequence floor. Monotonically increasing sequences prevent replay attacks &mdash; an attacker cannot re-serve an old envelope.</li>
      <li><strong>Bundle tokens.</strong> Verify the organization, environment, and node bundle tokens match the agent's assignment. An envelope for a different node or environment is rejected.</li>
      <li><strong>Public key fetch.</strong> Retrieve the signing public key from the control plane's JWKS endpoint (<code>/.well-known/devopsellence-desired-state-jwks.json</code>) by <code>key_id</code>.</li>
      <li><strong>RSA signature.</strong> Verify the RSA-PKCS1v15-SHA256 signature over the reconstructed signing input (format + bundle tokens + IDs + sequence + timestamps + payload hash).</li>
    </ol>

    <p>Only after all six checks pass does the agent proceed to pull images and start containers. A single failure at any step stops reconciliation for that cycle.</p>

    <h2>HSM-backed signing with Cloud KMS</h2>

    <p>The control plane manages two RSA signing keys: one for desired-state envelopes and one for identity tokens (used in Workload Identity, covered in <a href="<%= blog_post_path(slug: "gcp-primitives-part-4-identity") %>">Part 4</a>).</p>

    <p>In production, both keys live in Google Cloud KMS. The control plane calls the KMS API to sign:</p>

    <div class="terminal">
      <div class="terminal-bar">
        <span class="dot dot-red"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-yellow"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-green"></span>
        <span class="terminal-bar-title">KMS signing</span>
      </div>
      <div class="terminal-body">
        <pre class="config-pre"><code># Control plane requests signature from KMS:
POST /cloudkms/v1/{key_version}:asymmetricSign
  { "digest": { "sha256": "base64-hash" } }

# KMS computes signature inside HSM, returns it:
  { "signature": "base64-rsa-signature" }

# The raw private key never enters application memory.</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>This means even a full compromise of the control plane's application server doesn't expose the signing keys. An attacker can request signatures from KMS (if they have the application's credentials), but they cannot extract the private key material. Key rotation is a KMS operation, not a code deploy.</p>

    <p>Public keys are published via JWKS endpoints that agents and Google STS use for verification. Key IDs include a SHA256 prefix for unambiguous matching.</p>

    <h2>Immutable versioning in GCS</h2>

    <p>Each publish creates three GCS objects:</p>

    <div class="terminal">
      <div class="terminal-bar">
        <span class="dot dot-red"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-yellow"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-green"></span>
        <span class="terminal-bar-title">GCS object structure</span>
      </div>
      <div class="terminal-body">
        <pre class="config-pre"><code>gs://bucket/node-path/
  desired_state.json              # Direct envelope (mutable, backward compat)
  desired_state_pointer.json      # Pointer to latest immutable object
  desired-states/
    000000000001.json             # Immutable, sequence 1
    000000000002.json             # Immutable, sequence 2
    000000000003.json             # Immutable, sequence 3 (latest)</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>The immutable sequence objects are <strong>write-once</strong>. They are never modified after creation. This creates an append-only publish log that is tamper-evident by design. The pointer file references the latest immutable object. The direct envelope exists for backward compatibility during fleet upgrades.</p>

    <p>The publish order is deliberate: immutable object first, then direct envelope, then pointer. This ensures agents never see inconsistent state &mdash; the immutable object is fully written before anything references it.</p>

    <h2>Caching for resilience</h2>

    <p>Agents maintain three layers of cache so they survive outages without disruption:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>In-memory cache</strong> &mdash; the most recent verified state. Used when GCS returns the same object (ETag match).</li>
      <li><strong>Disk cache</strong> &mdash; persisted to <code>desired-state-cache.json</code>. Survives agent restarts.</li>
      <li><strong>Local override</strong> &mdash; operators can place a <code>desired-state-override.json</code> for emergency manual control.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>If GCS is temporarily unavailable, agents continue running from cached state. If the control plane goes down, agents don't notice &mdash; they read from GCS, not from the control plane. This is the core resilience property, covered in depth in <a href="<%= blog_post_path(slug: "gcp-primitives-part-6-resilience") %>">Part 6</a>.</p>

    <h2>Artifact Registry: image storage</h2>

    <p>Docker images are stored in Google Artifact Registry, organized per organization:</p>

    <div class="terminal">
      <div class="terminal-bar">
        <span class="dot dot-red"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-yellow"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-green"></span>
      </div>
      <div class="terminal-body">
        <pre class="config-pre"><code>us-docker.pkg.dev/{gcp-project}/ob-{org-token}-apps/{project}:{tag}</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p><strong>Push credentials</strong> are short-lived. When the CLI deploys, it requests push credentials from the control plane. The control plane issues a service account token (~20 minutes) scoped to the organization's GAR repository. No long-lived registry credentials are stored on developer machines.</p>

    <p><strong>Pull credentials</strong> use Workload Identity. The agent exchanges its short-lived GCP access token for an OAuth2 access token, then authenticates to Artifact Registry with <code>oauth2accesstoken</code> as the username. No Docker registry credentials are stored on your servers &mdash; tokens are obtained dynamically and expire automatically.</p>

    <p>Because images are in Artifact Registry, you get Google's global edge caching, independent availability from the control plane, and automatic regional replication. An image pulled once is cached in the regional replica closest to your node.</p>

    <h2>Summary</h2>

    <p>The deploy delivery pipeline uses three GCP services working together: <strong>Cloud KMS</strong> signs envelopes inside HSMs, <strong>Cloud Storage</strong> delivers them as immutable versioned objects, and <strong>Artifact Registry</strong> stores and serves Docker images with short-lived credentials. The control plane publishes and steps aside. Agents verify, pull, and reconcile independently.</p>

    <p>Next: <strong><%= link_to "Part 3 — Secrets that never touch the database", blog_post_path(slug: "gcp-primitives-part-3-secrets") %></strong></p>

  </article>

